node.text:
In this exhibition, Martinez combines miniature bas-reliefs, religious sculptures, reliquarios (relic holders), ex-votos, and anting-antings inside his museum boxes to create mini-retablos, altars and make-shift shrines.

The artists reinterprets these power objects that animistic societies used for
healing, rituals, divining destiny and as sources of good luck and protection. By putting these power objects together, Martinez focuses an appreciative lens on the syncretic nature of our culture, and invites us to explore the underlying belief systems which coexist in the melting pot that is the Filipino psyche.

CUSTODIAN OF POWER OBJECTS will be on view at Altro Mondo Creative Space (1159 Chino Roces Avenue, San Antonio Village, Makati City) until March 12 2022. The gallery is open from Tuesday to Saturday, 10am to 5pm. For inquiries, please contact us on Facebook (@altromondoart) or Instagram (@altromondoart). You can also message us via Viber or WhatsApp at 0917 888 7872.

Aldrin Olaguer renders these events through a filter of historical truth, despite the contradiction that painting is inherently subjective, and is a tool by which one can craft a narrative. In this dilemma, Olaguer invites the viewer to examine traces of his process, to look deeper into these iconographies, and ascertain the truth for themselves. 

HEROES EPIPHANY will be on view at Altro Mondo Creative Space (1159 Chino Roces Avenue, San Antonio Village, Makati City) until March 12 2022. The gallery is open from Tuesday to Saturday, 10am to 5pm.  For inquiries and viewing appointments, please contact us on Facebook (@altromondoart) or Instagram (@altromondoart). You can also message us via Viber or WhatsApp at 0917 888 7872.

Get to know more about Vincent Padilla and his works for his solo exhibition "Lying Between Critical Faults" at Altro Mondo Creative Space.

Lying Between Critical Faults is an exhibit that centers on the future representation of earth scenery from the impact of climate change, inspired by the artist’s most recent show “Romancing the inevitable.” 

Consequently, this exhibition focuses more on the impasse we are currently in. Utilizing a technique called paint pouring, a process that is known as a form of abstraction or non-representational art, the unpredictability of the technique merges to the artists intention of creating a depiction of the future. No discernible human intention or observable cause, the artist created a non-representational work that was made subjective.

— Vincent Padilla

LYING BETWEEN CRITICAL FAULTS will be on view at Altro Mondo Creative Space (1159 Chino Roces Avenue, San Antonio Village, Makati City) until March 12 2022. The gallery is open from Tuesday to Saturday, 10am to 5pm. For inquiries and bookings, please contact us on Facebook (@altromondoart) or Instagram (@altromondoart). You can also message us via Viber or WhatsApp at 0917 888 7872.

Chad Montero revisits the local legends and fables he encountered as a child, re-examining the veracity of their purported moral lessons in his work for the exhibit. In "Karera," he tackles the story of the Kuneho and Pagong (Hare and the Tortoise). 

In the real world, there is no moral narrative safeguard that ensures that the good guys "win." More often than not, it is the "pagongs" that lose and fall victim to circumstance to the benefit of the "kunehos" of the world. Montero renders this by turning the story on its head, depicting the hare conquering the tortoise on its way to victory. 

Click the link to view our virtual exhibit: https://artspaces.kunstmatrix.com/en/exhibition/9202691/on-making-god-laugh

On Making God Laugh will be on view at Altro Mondo Creative Space (1159 Chino Roces Avenue, San Antonio Village, Makati City) until February 12 2022. The gallery is open from Tuesday to Saturday, 10am to 5pm. For inquiries, please contact us on Facebook (@altromondoart) or Instagram (@altromondoart). Floyd Absalon takes inspiration from his local community, and in particular, from his neighbor's plant collection which blossomed during the pandemic.

His work "I Only Knew A Straight Line Before I Met You" features a large, psychedelic leaf against a multicolored background. Absalon plays with the meaning of both symmetry and asymmetry between the image in the foreground and background. Its title alludes to a line in Les Miserables that resonated with Absalon.

"Before him he saw two roads, both equally straight; but he did see two; and that terrified him— he who had never in his life known anything but one straight line. And, bitter anguish, these two roads were contradictory." — Les Miserables, Victor Hugo

Adeo Sta. Juana's work balances meticulous composition with playful digression, which is no more evident than in his piece titled "Trio Attempting Normalcy." The work is a free-wheeling collaboration between Sta. Juana, his wife Magi, and their daughter Chaouen, combining frenetic scribbles and child-like imagery to create a dynamic work of art. 

The piece, like the rest of Sta. Juana's work in the exhibit, serves as a visual metaphor for how the best laid plans are still subject to the inevitable yet delightful uncertainties of life.

node.text:
Ideals are like the stars: we never reach them, but like the mariners of the sea, we chart our course by them. Self-taught artist Joar Songcuya continues his saga at sea with his exciting new works presented by Altro Mondo Creative Space and wonderfully curated by Ricky Francisco. 

Songcuya’s strength is in the way he has convincingly formulated a unique artistic language. His works establish their own symbolic universe, mixing personal memory, loss and desire, pointing to the negotiation and transgression of limits between art and the everyday experience at sea.

The Sea Is Not A Quiet Place will be on view at Altro Mondo Creative Space (1159 Chino Roces Avenue, San Antonio Village, Makati City) until February 12 2022. The gallery is open from Tuesday to Saturday, 10am to 5pm. Viewings are strictly by appointment. For inquiries, please contact us on Facebook (@altromondoart) or Instagram (@altromondoart). node.text:
Andre Baldovino's "Nightwing" takes inspiration from the famous Rorschach test, which requires test subjects to interpret inkblots. As an abstract painter, Baldovino is fascinated with how people interpret seemingly random shapes in non-representational work. 

The piece was made by pouring ink on 50 individual pieces of paper, then folding them to create a symmetrical image. Baldovino then designed a symmetrical wooden sculpture that incorporates patterns revealed through the folded pieces of paper. 

The resulting design is akin to a winged insect, but just like the Rorshach test, its true essence is elusive and any attempts at interpretation say more about us than the objects we attempt to interpret.

The Sea is Not A Quiet Place is the titular pièce de résistance in Songcuya's exhibit. The work encapsulates the visual magnetism that underscores the rest of the works in the exhibit. In the piece, Songcuya masterfully controls every hue of blue, mixing crimson and grey tones to highlight the fury of the raging sea. These techniques call to mind the great watercolour and ink abstractions of that renegade Chinese Modernist, Zhang Da-Quian.
